# A basic Vagrantfile to test AWS with Chef using Docker.
# This uses an Ubuntu 18.04 image from Hashicorp Atlas.
# Requires 'docker-machine' and 'docker' be installed on your host before using this file.
#
# To use this vagrant box:
# 1) Copy the file to a directory (i.e /Users/vagrant/project/) in a git repository. Make sure you're using a clean, unmodified copy. Otherwise you'll run into problems.
# 2) Open Terminal and go to that directory. Use 'vagrant up' to create a virtual machine for running Chef.
# 3) Wait until it reports the following: vagrant ssh; vagrant status
# 4) If all goes well, ssh into the Vagrant box using 'vagrant ssh'. Use 'chef-client --version' command in the shell prompt on the remote host. You should see version 13 of Chef installed on the Vagrant box.
# 5) Connect to EC2 (us-west-2). Find your instance ID with 'aws ec2 describe-instances' and then use it as an IP address for ssh. For example: ssh -i /Users/username/.ssh/keypair.pem centos@ec2-xx-yy-zz-ww.compute-1.amazonaws.com
# 6) Use 'sudo su' command on the remote box to become root. Then, run '/etc/rc.d/init.d/chef-client status'. You should see something similar to the following:
# [root@ip-172-31-45-181 ~]# sudo su
# [root@ip-172-31-45-181 vagrant]# /etc/rc.d/init.d/chef-client status
# This program is currently not running....
# To start the program now, run  (as root) service chef-client start.
# ...done.
# [root@ip-172-31-45-181 vagrant]# /etc/rc.d/init.d/chef-client status
# chef-client is running...
# [root@ip-172-31-45-181 vagrant]#
# 7) On the remote host run 'exit' command to return to your shell prompt and back to your Vagrant box. Then use 'vagrant ssh' again from your local host to connect with the Chef server instance (i.e., EC2 instance). The remote server should be configured with all required cookbooks. To verify, on the remote host in a terminal window use 'sudo chef-client --version'. This should return something similar to 13.0 or higher.
# 8) In a browser window, point your browser at the IP address of any EC2 instance that is part of the group. It will be configured by Chef and have its own hostname which you can use in place of the IP address as long as it is resolvable from another network. To find this, ssh into the box with 'vagrant ssh' and then 'curl ifconfig.co' to get the public DNS name assigned for the instance.
# 9) Return to Vagrant box shell prompt (i.e., 'vagrant ssh'). Run 'exit'. Return back to your local host by running 'vagrant ssh'. When it asks you to confirm, type 'yes' and hit enter.
# 10) Verify that an EC2 instance is now registered in the AWS auto-scaling group. Use the IP address from (7) above. For example: 'curl http://ip-address' or 'curl ec2-xx-yy-zz-ww.us-west-2.compute.amazonaws.com'. This should result in a 200 status response on the page indicating that Chef is running successfully and the application is deployed.
# 11) Use the same curl command with --include option to include headers for additional information. You can also find this information using 'aws ec2 describe-instances --instance-ids xxx --query 'Reservations[*].Instances[*].InstanceId'. Note that the ID used in (30), (79) and (118) above is different from the value in (45). Replace xxx with the ID you get here. It should be something like this: aws ec2 describe-instances --instance-ids i-0044a749c36b55d43 --query 'Reservations[*].Instances[*].InstanceId'. You can copy/paste the value from (1).
# 12) Use the same curl command with --include option to include headers for additional information. The IP address from (10) above will change based on time. So, ssh into the instance and then check /etc/sysconfig/network-scripts folder. Look at the contents of the 'ifcfg-eth0' file in the ifcfg-eth0.save file to find out your public DNS name assigned by AWS.
# 13) Use curl command with --include option as above on a browser to see that response is OK, and then use curl with --header option (this option will give more information than the --include option). For example: curl http://ec2-xx-yy-zz-ww.us-west-2.compute.amazonaws.com -I
# 14) Use 'sudo tail -f /var/log/chef/client.log' command in a separate terminal window on the Vagrant box to watch the chef-client.log file. You'll see entries that look like this:
